\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
This policy formalizes how decision-making power — both operational and administrative — is assigned,
 delegated,
 and exercised within the Information Operations Department.
 The separation of administrative and operational authority is designed to preserve continuity,
 accountability,
 and appropriate oversight across the Information Technology function while ensuring that mandatory security controls are never subordinated to administrative convenience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.1 Authority Classification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Authority within the Information Operations Department is classified into two distinct categories to satisfy NIST SP 800-53 Rev.
 5:
 AC-5 (Separation of Duties):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Administrative Authority
\series default
:
 Managerial oversight functions including personnel management,
 timekeeping,
 budget approval,
 and policy ratification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Operational Authority
\series default
:
 Technical decision-making functions including infrastructure management,
 cybersecurity configuration,
 technical standards,
 and service design.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Constraint
\series default
:
 Dual authority (the ability to exercise both administrative and operational functions) resides inherently with the IT Director and may only be granted to others through explicit,
 written delegation (including the standing delegation defined in Section 6.2).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Clarification
\series default
:
 Mandatory security controls — defined as all requirements stipulated by the CJIS Security Policy,
 Nevada Revised Statutes,
 and County-adopted security baselines — shall not be subject to override by administrative stand-ins.
 The IT Director shall ensure that mandatory security controls are maintained regardless of personnel changes or delegations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
CJIS Management Control
\series default
:
 For systems processing,
 storing,
 or transmitting Criminal Justice Information (CJI),
 decision rights are subject to the applicable CJIS Management Control Agreement and shall not be overridden by administrative stand-ins.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Delegation Rules and Limitations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Formal Documentation
\series default
:
 The IT Director shall delegate operational authority only to technically qualified personnel (Tier L3 or higher per 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.07"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Workforce Roles,
 Responsibilities,
 and Competency Framework)) and shall document each delegation in writing.
 The IT Director shall define the scope,
 conditions,
 and duration in the delegation record.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Annual Review
\series default
:
 The IT Director shall review delegated authority and privileged access assignments at least annually to validate continued business need,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section AC-6(7) (Least Privilege — Review of User Privileges).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Retention
\series default
:
 The IT Director shall retain delegation records in the Department's designated system of record in accordance with NRS 239.125 and the Nevada Local Government Records Management Program.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Standing Delegation
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director holds standing delegated operational authority and is authorized to exercise administrative functions in the IT Director's absence only within the bounds of a standing written Delegation of Authority Order,
 reviewed annually.
 The Assistant IT Director shall exercise only those administrative functions explicitly delegated in writing by the IT Director.
 Authority not expressly granted is reserved to the IT Director.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Scope of Administrative Authority
\series default
:
 Authority is limited to routine operational administration (e.g.,
 timecard approvals,
 workflow coordination,
 internal purchasing).
 It does not include authority for HR disciplinary actions,
 terminations,
 or ratification of the Countywide IT budget.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Lapse
\series default
:
 Failure to complete the annual review of the standing Delegation of Authority Order shall not automatically revoke the standing delegation,
 but shall constitute non-compliance subject to remediation under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:5.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 The IT Director shall complete the overdue review within ten (10) business days of discovery,
 and the delegation record shall be flagged as review-past-due in the Department's system of record until remediation is complete.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Directed Deputization
\series default
:
 The IT Director may designate any Tier L3+ IT Department personnel to exercise specific operational authority on the IT Director's behalf for a defined scope and duration.
 Directed Deputization is limited to operational functions — including work order management,
 priority retasking,
 and representation in meetings — and shall not include administrative authority as defined in Section 6.1.
 The IT Director shall document the designation in writing,
 specifying the scope of authority granted,
 the duration,
 and any constraints.
 Directed Deputization does not displace the Assistant IT Director from their current role,
 modify their standing delegation,
 or alter the chain of delegation established in this policy.
 The IT Director retains authority to rescind any Directed Deputization at any time.
 Directed Deputization shall not include:
 policy exception approval,
 formal risk acceptance,
 incident declaration authority (unless separately authorized under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
),
 access approval for the delegate's own account,
 or any function prohibited by the Separation of Duties Matrix maintained under Section 6.6.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Emergency Operational Authority
\series default
:
 During declared cybersecurity incidents (per 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
),
 all operational authority transfers immediately and exclusively to the designated Incident Commander.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Declaration Authority
\series default
:
 Authority to declare a cybersecurity incident resides with the IT Director,
 Assistant IT Director,
 or designated technical lead as defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Incident Commander Qualification — Designated Appointment
\series default
:
 The IT Director may designate any IT Department staff member as Incident Commander for a specific incident.
 Designation shall be made at the time it becomes effective and documented in the incident record.
 No tier-level prerequisite applies to a designated appointment.
 The IT Director retains authority to rescind any designation and resume the Incident Commander role at any time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Incident Commander Qualification — Emergency Declaration Authority
\series default
:
 When both the IT Director and the Assistant IT Director are genuinely unavailable,
 authority to declare a cybersecurity incident and serve as Incident Commander shall be limited to Tier L3+ IT Department personnel identified in writing by the IT Director.
 The IT Director shall maintain this list and review it at least annually.
 In all cases,
 the Incident Commander shall be an IT Department staff member.
 Personnel serving in a non-technical administrative or acting capacity are not eligible to serve as Incident Commander under either path.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Non-Interference
\series default
:
 Administrative stand-ins shall not intervene in,
 delay,
 or countermand operational directives issued by the Incident Commander.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Emergency Procurement
\series default
:
 Emergency operational actions and procurement necessary to maintain or restore mandated security controls shall not be delayed for administrative convenience;
 unresolved funding disputes shall be escalated to the Board of County Commissioners without pausing required containment actions.
 The Incident Commander is authorized to initiate emergency procurement using County emergency procedures with after-the-fact ratification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Fiscal Duty
\series default
:
 Fiscal Affairs and Purchasing shall process Incident Commander emergency procurement requests using applicable emergency procedures without delaying required containment or mandated control restoration.
 Fiscal Affairs and Purchasing shall document all actions and approvals in the incident record.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Constraint
\series default
:
 Administrative funding authority shall not be exercised to delay,
 suspend,
 or condition execution of incident containment actions or mandated security control implementation.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Administrative Stand-ins
\series default
:
 Non-technical leadership (e.g.,
 County Manager) acting as a stand-in during leadership absence may fulfill administrative duties (e.g.,
 communications coordination,
 staffing logistics,
 budget routing) but shall not:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Issue operational directives,
 service restoration sequencing instructions,
 or countermand technical decisions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Authorize changes to security baselines,
 firewall rules,
 or access configurations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Approve risk acceptance for mandatory security controls.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Modify patch deployment schedules or vulnerability remediation priorities.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Interdepartmental Boundaries
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
To preserve operational integrity and separation of duties,
 the following boundaries shall apply:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Human Resources (HR)
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
HR may enforce administrative actions (e.g.,
 terminations) and shall provide official notifications per Section 6.5.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
HR shall not influence how access revocation is performed,
 dictate tools,
 or establish technical response timelines without IT Director approval.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Fiscal Affairs
\series default
:
 Fiscal Affairs may control budgetary limits but shall not mandate hardware standards or compel the reduction of mandatory security controls due to cost without a formal risk acceptance documented in the Risk Register maintained under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Risk Management Policy) and signed by the IT Director.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
System Access Restrictions
\series default
:
 To enforce separation of duties (AC-5),
 non-IT personnel serving as administrative stand-ins shall not be granted administrative access to Information Operations systems (e.g.,
 Active Directory,
 firewalls),
 including "break-glass" accounts,
 or physical access to secure server environments without IT escort.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Facilities Access
\series default
:
 Facilities and custodial access provisioning for server rooms/network closets shall be controlled by Information Operations access lists;
 emergency entry by non-IT personnel shall require IT escort or the Incident Commander's written authorization.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Revocation and Escalation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Revocability
\series default
:
 The IT Director may revoke any delegated authority at any time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Conflict Resolution
\series default
:
 The IT Director or the party identifying the conflict shall formally escalate disputes between administrative and operational authority to the County Manager for mediation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Mediation Constraints
\series default
:
 Mediation shall occur on an expedited basis and begin within one (1) business day of escalation.
 Mediation may address priorities and resources but shall not authorize deviation from mandatory security controls or security baselines.
 The IT Director or Incident Commander shall ensure that operational containment and mandated control implementation continue during mediation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Impartiality
\series default
:
 If the County Manager is serving as the administrative stand-in and is a party to the conflict,
 the IT Director shall escalate the matter to the Board of County Commissioners to ensure impartial review.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Delegated Notification Authority
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Information Operations Department designates Human Resources as the authoritative originator of official onboarding and offboarding notifications.
 This delegation is procedural — HR is authorized to initiate the process — but does not convey control over access implementation,
 technical execution timing,
 or operational response,
 which remain with the IT Director and designated IT personnel.
 When HR is unavailable and an urgent separation requires immediate action,
 the County Manager or other legally authorized official may initiate the notification directly to the Information Operations Department.
 The IT Director shall treat such notifications as valid and shall document the source and circumstances in the Department's system of record.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Timelines
\series default
:
 HR shall provide:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Onboarding notifications
\series default
:
 At least three (3) business days prior to the start date.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Offboarding notifications
\series default
:
 Immediately upon determination of separation (no later than close of business on the decision date).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Accountability
\series default
:
 The IT Director shall document notification delays that result in access control violations and report them to the County Manager.
 The delaying party bears accountability for the resulting compliance gap.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 Separation of Specific Duties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director shall enforce the following separation of duties requirements to satisfy NIST SP 800-53 AC-5 (Separation of Duties):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Access Approval vs.
 Access Provisioning
\series default
:
 Personnel authorized to approve access requests shall not be the same personnel who implement the access in the directory service,
 except where automated provisioning systems enforced by policy are utilized.
 Automated systems must enforce approval workflows and maintain immutable audit trails.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Security Administration vs.
 Audit Logging
\series default
:
 Personnel with administrative control over security baselines (e.g.,
 firewall rules) shall not have the ability to modify or delete audit logs that record their actions.
 Security logs must be forwarded to a repository where security administrators hold read-only or append-only privileges.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Development vs.
 Production
\series default
:
 Personnel shall not have unmonitored administrative access to both development and production environments for the same system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Change Approval vs.
 Change Implementation
\series default
:
 Personnel authorized to approve significant changes to security baselines (e.g.,
 firewall policy,
 Group Policy,
 endpoint protection) shall not be the same personnel who implement those changes,
 except where emergency procedures are invoked and subsequently reviewed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Separation Matrix
\series default
:
 The IT Director shall maintain a documented Separation of Duties Matrix identifying specific incompatible duties,
 including but not limited to:
 (a) system administration vs.
 audit log review;
 (b) access provisioning vs.
 access approval.
 The IT Director shall review this matrix annually.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Delegation Constraint
\series default
:
 Delegation shall not permit any individual to both request and approve access,
 approve access for themselves,
 or combine access approval with access provisioning,
 in accordance with separation of duties (AC-5) and least privilege (AC-6).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director shall document separation-of-duties role assignments and corresponding privileged access authorizations in the Department's access control matrix and shall enforce them through role-based access control (RBAC).
 The IT Director shall review the access control matrix at least annually and upon significant role or staffing changes.
 When the IT Director determines that staffing constraints require a single individual to perform otherwise incompatible duties,
 the IT Director shall implement compensating controls (e.g.,
 independent after-the-fact review within one (1) business day,
 immutable logging,
 or secondary approval via workflow) and shall document the exception.
\end_layout

\end_body
